ce:section.ce:para:
A B-CD with a single emission peak was synthesized using a simple microwave approach with citric acid and urea as precursors. The change in fluorescence intensity was measured according to the anion species to determine whether the prepared B-CD exhibited a selective fluorescence change with respect to the perrhenate anion (Fig. 7
                        ). At an excitation wavelength of 254 nm, the maximum emission of the B-CD was observed at 450 nm. The B-CD and anion were mixed with concentrations of 25 ppm and 50 mM, respectively, to obtain an aqueous solution. Fig. 7(a) depicts the effect of several types of anions on fluorescence. As indicated in the figure, B-CD exhibited a significant decrease in fluorescence intensity with respect to the perrhenate and iodide anions. However, the decrease in the fluorescence intensity was small for other anions, such as Cl−, HCO3
                        −, CH3COO−, CN−, and F−. The experimental results confirm the selectivity of B-CD with respect to perrhenate and iodide anions.

The aforementioned experiments verify that the perrhenate anion exhibits various fluorescence characteristics in CQD aqueous solutions depending on the excitation wavelengths. The UV–Vis absorbance of seven different types of anionic aqueous solutions (50 mM) was measured to further understand this phenomenon. Both perrhenate and iodide anions absorbed light with wavelengths of less than 300 and 260 nm, respectively (Fig. 9
                        ). During the fluorescence experiments, the fluorescence intensity decreased rapidly when an aqueous solution containing the perrhenate anion was stimulated using light with wavelengths of 254 and 275 nm. This implies that excitation wavelengths shorter than 300 nm are likely absorbed by the perrhenate anion, preventing the CQDs from attaining the excited state (Figs. 7 and 8). The type of CQDs employed (B-CD or D-CD) did not impact the fluorescence reduction phenomenon. When the B-CD aqueous solution with anions was excited at 254 nm, the aqueous solution with anions that did not absorb this wavelength (Cl−, HCO3
                        −, CH3COO−, CN−, and F−) exhibited nearly no decrease in fluorescence (Fig. 7(a)). The inner filter effect reduces the fluorescence intensity owing to the overlap of the excitation wavelength of the fluorescence (CQDs in this case) with the absorption wavelength of the quencher (anions in this case) [31]. However, no change was observed in the fluorescence intensity when the mixed solution of D-CD and perrhenate anion was excited at a wavelength of 350 nm, which was larger than the absorption wavelength of the perrhenate anion (Fig. 8(c)).

The UV–Vis absorbance of the C-CD aqueous solution (25 ppm), perrhenate anion aqueous solution (50 mM), and C-CD aqueous solution containing perrhenate anions were evaluated to understand the detection mechanism of the perrhenate anion. No significant difference was observed in the absorption wavelength between the C-CD aqueous solution containing high concentrations of the perrhenate anion and the perrhenate anion aqueous solution (Fig. 13
                        ). This implies that C-CD and perrhenate anions do not form a non-fluorescent complex in the ground state. Nevertheless, when C-CD was stimulated with light at a wavelength of 350 nm, a considerable reduction in fluorescence intensity and color change were observed. This indicates that an interaction occurred between the C-CD of the excited state and the perrhenate anion. This electron transfer mechanism from an excited phosphor to an acceptor can be described as photoinduced electron transfer (PET) [32]. The cationic surface functional groups of C-CD are capable of exhibiting electrostatic interactions with perrhenate anions. Particularly, perrhenate anions have a larger molecular size than common anions, such as Cl−. According to the concept of Hofmeister selectivity, larger anions are more easily adsorbed on larger cations, such as the quaternary ammonium functional groups used in this study [33]. Additionally, the perrhenate anion is expected to serve as a base, forming a hydrogen bond with the surface functional groups of C-CD [7]. The perrhenate anion interacts with C-CD throughout these processes, reducing the fluorescence intensity in the emission wavelength range of up to 540 nm. Fig. 14
                         depicts the reduction mechanism of C-CD fluorescence caused by the perrhenate anion.
